## Period 1

Hydrogen (H)
Hydrogen is the universe's simplest and most abundant element. With just one proton in its nucleus and a single electron orbiting this core, hydrogen stands as the foundational block of all chemical elements.

Helium (He)
Helium, with two protons in its nucleus, is the second lightest and second most abundant element in the observable universe. Known for its lack of color, taste, and odor, helium is a noble gas that does not chemically react under most conditions. It is primarily used in cryogenics, particularly in cooling superconducting magnets, and as a lifting gas in balloons and airships.

## Period 2

Lithium (Li)
Lithium, the lightest metal and the third element on the periodic table, has three protons in its nucleus. It is a soft, silvery-white alkali metal that reacts swiftly with water and air, necessitating its storage under oil or in an inert atmosphere. Lithium is widely used in rechargeable batteries for electronics, in mood-stabilizing drugs, and in heat-resistant glass and ceramics.

Beryllium (Be)
Beryllium, with four protons in its nucleus, is a hard, gray metal that is remarkably strong and lightweight. This element is classified as an alkaline earth metal and is non-magnetic, resistant to concentrated nitric acid, and has one of the highest melting points of the light metals. Beryllium is extensively used as an alloying agent in aerospace materials, in nuclear reactors as a neutron moderator, and in various precision instruments.

Boron (B)
Boron, the fifth element, consists of five protons in its nucleus. It is a metalloid with unique properties, being neither a metal nor a non-metal. Boron is hard, yet has a different crystalline form that is soft. It is an essential nutrient for plants, and its compounds are used in glassmaking, detergents, and as semiconductors in electronics.

Carbon (C)
Carbon, with six protons in its nucleus, is a fundamental element of life, classified as a nonmetal. It has several allotropes, including diamond, graphite, and the recently discovered fullerenes, each exhibiting unique properties. Carbon forms more compounds than any other element and plays a crucial role in the Earth's carbon cycle. It is vital in the chemical industry and is the basis of organic chemistry.

Nitrogen (N)
Nitrogen, making up about 78% of the Earth's atmosphere, has seven protons in its nucleus. This nonmetal is a colorless, odorless, and tasteless gas at room temperature. Nitrogen is essential for all living organisms, forming part of the molecular structure of proteins and nucleic acids. It is used industrially in the manufacture of fertilizers, explosives, and as a refrigerant.

Oxygen (O)
Oxygen, with eight protons in its nucleus, is essential for life as the driver of cellular respiration. This element is a highly reactive nonmetal, forming oxides with almost all other elements and compounds. Oxygen makes up about 21% of the Earth's atmosphere and is used in medical applications, metal cutting, and welding, as well as in the production of steel and plastics.

Fluorine (F)
Fluorine, the most electronegative and reactive of all elements, has nine protons in its nucleus. This pale yellow gas is extremely toxic and corrosive, reacting with almost all organic and inorganic substances. Fluorine is used in the manufacture of uranium hexafluoride for nuclear reactors, sulfur hexafluoride, and in the production of Teflon and other fluoropolymers.

Neon (Ne)
Neon, with ten protons in its nucleus, is a colorless, inert noble gas under standard conditions. Known for its distinctive red-orange glow in neon lighting, neon is one of the noble gases that does not form compounds with other elements under normal conditions. It is used in high-voltage indicators, vacuum tubes, and as a cryogenic refrigerant.

## Period 3


Sodium (Na)
Sodium, with eleven protons in its nucleus, is a soft, silvery-white, highly reactive metal belonging to the alkali metal group. It reacts vigorously with water, producing hydrogen gas and sodium hydroxide, hence it is stored under oil or in an inert atmosphere. Sodium is essential for life, playing a key role in regulating blood volume and blood pressure. It is also used in the manufacture of glass, paper, soap, and textiles.

Magnesium (Mg)
Magnesium, containing twelve protons in its nucleus, is a shiny gray solid. This alkaline earth metal is lightweight and moderately hard. Magnesium is highly flammable, especially when powdered or shaved into thin strips, though it is difficult to ignite in mass or bulk. It is used in the manufacture of aircraft and missile construction, as a reducing agent in the production of uranium, and in flash photography.

Aluminum (Al)
Aluminum, with thirteen protons in its nucleus, is a soft, durable, lightweight, ductile, and malleable metal with appearance ranging from silvery to dull gray. It is nonmagnetic and does not easily ignite. Aluminum is the third most abundant element and the most abundant metal in the Earth's crust. It is used in a vast array of products including cans, foils, kitchen utensils, window frames, beer kegs, and airplane parts due to its low density and ability to resist corrosion.

Silicon (Si)
Silicon, containing fourteen protons in its nucleus, is a hard, crystalline solid with a blue-grey metallic lustre. It is a metalloid, meaning it has properties of both metals and non-metals. Silicon is the second most abundant element in the Earth's crust after oxygen. It is used primarily in semiconductors and solar cells, as well as in silicones, a diverse family of synthetic materials used in everything from lubricants to medical implants.

Phosphorus (P)
Phosphorus, with fifteen protons in its nucleus, is a nonmetal that exists in several forms, or allotropes, including white, red, and black. White phosphorus is highly reactive, glows in the dark, and is used in military applications and pyrotechnics. Red phosphorus is used in matches, fireworks, and as a flame retardant. Black phosphorus is the least reactive allotrope and is used in certain high-pressure applications.

Sulfur (S)
Sulfur, containing sixteen protons in its nucleus, is a bright yellow crystalline solid at room temperature. Known for its distinct smell, often likened to rotten eggs, sulfur is nonmetallic and not soluble in water. It is an essential element for life, involved in the amino acid and protein synthesis. Industrially, sulfur is used in the production of sulfuric acid, which is perhaps the most important chemical manufactured by western civilizations, and in vulcanization of rubber.

Chlorine (Cl)
Chlorine, with seventeen protons in its nucleus, is a halogen that appears as a greenish-yellow gas at room temperature. It has a pungent, irritating odor and is extremely dangerous, capable of displacing oxygen in the bloodstream. Chlorine is widely used as a disinfectant in water treatment and swimming pools, in the production of a wide range of consumer goods, including paper products, dyestuffs, textiles, petroleum products, medicines, antiseptics, insecticides, food, solvents, and paints.

Argon (Ar)
Argon, containing eighteen protons in its nucleus, is an odorless, colorless, tasteless, and nontoxic gas. As a noble gas, it is inert under most conditions and forms no stable compounds at room temperature. Argon is the third-most abundant gas in the Earth's atmosphere. It is used in fluorescent lights and other types of gas discharge tubes, as an inert gas shield for arc welding and cutting, as a blanket for the production of titanium and other reactive elements, and as a protective atmosphere for growing silicon and germanium crystals.

## Period 4


Potassium (K)
Potassium, with nineteen protons in its nucleus, is a soft, silvery-white metal that is highly reactive, especially in water, creating hydrogen gas and heat. It is an alkali metal that is essential for life, particularly for heart function and muscle contraction. Potassium compounds are used in fertilizers, soap making, and glass production.

Calcium (Ca)
Calcium, containing twenty protons in its nucleus, is a reactive, soft gray metal and the fifth-most abundant element by mass in the Earth's crust. It is essential for living organisms, particularly in cell physiology, and is the major material used in the shells of marine organisms, snails, and eggshells. Calcium compounds are widely used in the construction industry, in lime as a chemical feedstock, and in the manufacture of cement and plaster.

Scandium (Sc)
Scandium, with twenty-one protons in its nucleus, is a soft, silvery metallic element that, when exposed to air, develops a slightly yellowish or pinkish cast. It is often classified as a rare earth element and is used in small amounts in alloys for aerospace and other high-technology applications.

Titanium (Ti)
Titanium, containing twenty-two protons in its nucleus, is a strong, lustrous, corrosion-resistant (including to sea water and chlorine) metal with a silver color. It is as strong as steel but much less dense. It is used in strong, lightweight alloys (most notably with iron and aluminum), and its compounds are widely used in sunscreens and pigments.

Vanadium (V)
Vanadium, with twenty-three protons in its nucleus, is a hard, silvery-grey, malleable transition metal. The elemental metal is rarely found in nature, but once isolated artificially, the formation of an oxide layer stabilizes the free metal against further oxidation. Vanadium is used as an additive to steel to increase strength and with titanium to make high-speed airframes.

Chromium (Cr)
Chromium, containing twenty-four protons in its nucleus, is a steely-grey, lustrous, hard, and brittle transition metal. It is the principal element in stainless steel, which is used to make cutlery, and because of its high corrosion resistance and hardness, chromium metal is also used in chrome plating and alloying for production of corrosion-resistant superalloys.

Manganese (Mn)
Manganese, with twenty-five protons in its nucleus, is a silvery-gray metal that looks similar to iron. It is hard and very brittle, difficult to fuse, but easy to oxidize. Manganese metal and its common ions are paramagnetic. It is used in steel production to improve hardness, stiffness, and strength. It is also used in the production of batteries and ferrites.

Iron (Fe)
Iron, containing twenty-six protons in its nucleus, is the most common element on Earth by mass, forming much of Earth's outer and inner core. It is the fourth most common element in the Earth's crust. Its abundance in rocky planets like Earth is due to its abundant production by fusion in high-mass stars. Iron is an essential element for blood production and is used industrially to make steel, amongst many other uses.

Cobalt (Co)
Cobalt, with twenty-seven protons in its nucleus, is a hard, lustrous, silver-gray metal. It is found naturally only in chemically combined form. The metal has magnetic properties. Cobalt-based blue pigments have been used since ancient times for jewelry and paints, and miners have long used the name kobold ore for some minerals. Cobalt is used in the preparation of magnetic, wear-resistant, and high-strength alloys.

Nickel (Ni)
Nickel, containing twenty-eight protons in its nucleus, is a silvery-white lustrous metal with a slight golden tinge. Nickel belongs to the transition metals and is hard and ductile. It is used in many industrial and consumer products, including stainless steel, magnets, coinage, rechargeable batteries, electric guitar strings, microphone capsules, and special alloys.

Copper (Cu)
Copper, with twenty-nine protons in its nucleus, is a soft, malleable, and ductile metal with very high thermal and electrical conductivity. A freshly exposed surface of pure copper has a pinkish-orange color. Copper is used as a conductor of heat and electricity, as a building material, and as a constituent of various metal alloys, such as sterling silver used in jewelry and cupronickel used to make marine hardware and coins.

Zinc (Zn)
Zinc, containing thirty protons in its nucleus, is a slightly brittle metal at room temperature and has a silvery-greyish appearance when oxidation is removed. It is the first element in group 12 of the periodic table. Zinc is used to galvanize iron and steel to protect against rust, in making brass

## Period 5


